						th<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T171958-0500"?>e<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T171958-0500" content="a"?>n
						we know for certain that B cannot occur (since they are
						disjoint)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172008-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
						which means that P(B)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172013-0500"?>
						<?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172014-0500"?>
						<?oxy_insert_end?>0. We therefore see that if
						<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T173545-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T173543-0500" content="two"?>
						events are disjoint,
						<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172036-0500" content="knowing that "?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172048-0500"?>the
						fact that <?oxy_insert_end?>one event occurs changes the probability that
						the other
						<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172055-0500"?>will
						<?oxy_insert_end?>occur<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172059-0500" content="s"?>
						to 0. This means that the
						<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172111-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172110-0500" content="two"?>
